          <task xml:id="exer_evenoddaddb">
            <p>
              If <m>x</m> is an even integer and <m>y</m> is an odd integer,
              then <m>x + y</m> is an odd integer.
            </p>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>x</m> is an odd integer and <m>y</m> is an odd integer,
              then <m>x + y</m> is an even integer.
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                We assume that <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are odd integers and will prove that 
                <m>x+y</m> is an even integer.  Since <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are odd, there exist 
                integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such that
                <m>x = 2m + 1</m> and <m>y = 2n+1</m>. Then
                <md>
                  <mrow>x + y \amp = \left( 2m + 1 \right) + \left( 2n + 1 \right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = 2m + 2n + 2</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = 2 \left( m + n + 1 \right)</mrow>
                </md>.
                Since the integers are closed under addition, <m>\left( m + n + 1 \right)</m> is 
                an integer, and hence the last equation shows that <m>x + y</m> is even. 
                Therefore, we have proven that if <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are odd integers, 
                then <m>x+y</m> is an even integer.
              </p>
