    <exercise xml:id="exer_5m_7">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Construct a know-show table and write a complete proof for each of the following statements:
        </p>
      </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>m</m> is an even integer,
              then <m>5m + 7</m> is an odd integer.
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                We assume that <m>m</m> is an even integer and will prove that <m>5m + 7</m> 
                is an odd integer.  Since <m>m</m> is an even integer, there exists an 
                integer <m>k</m> such that <m>m = 2k</m>.  Using substitution and algebra, 
                we see that
                <md>
                  <mrow>5m + 7 \amp = 5(2k) + 7</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = 10k + 6 + 1</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = 2(5k + 3) + 1</mrow>
                </md>
                By the closure properties of the integers, we conclude that <m>5k + 3</m> is 
                an integer, and so the last equation proves that <m>5m + 7</m> is an odd integer.
              </p>
              <p>
                Another proof. By <xref ref="exer_evenoddadda"/> of <xref ref="exer_evenoddadd"></xref>, 
                <m>5m</m> is an even integer.  Hence, by <xref ref="exer_evenoddaddb"/> of
                <xref ref="exer_evenoddadd"></xref>, <m>5m + 7</m> is an even integer.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task>
            <p>
              If <m>m</m> is an odd integer,
              then <m>5m + 7</m> is an even integer.
            </p>
          </task>
          <task>
            <p>
              If <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are odd integers,
              then <m>mn + 7</m> is an even integer.
            </p>
