          proof for each of the following statements:
        </p>
      </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are both type 1 integers,
              then <m>a + b</m> is a type 2 integer.
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be integers and assume that <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are 
                both type 1 integers.  Then, there exist integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such 
                that <m>a = 3m + 1</m> and <m>b = 3n + 1</m>.  Now show that
                <me>
                  a + b = 3 \left( m + n \right) + 2
                </me>.
                The closure properties of the integers imply that <m>m + n</m> is an integer. 
                Therefore, the last equation tells us that <m>a + b</m> is a type 2 integer. 
                Hence, we have proved that if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are both type 1 integers, 
                then <m>a + b</m> is a type 2 integer.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task>
